'''Diljit Singh Rana, Baron Rana''', [[MBE]] (born 20 September 1938) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician and member of the [[House of Lords]]. He was married to Lady Shruti Rana. 

In June 2004, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Rana''', of Malone in the [[County Antrim|County of Antrim]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.com/pa/ld200304/ldjournal/237/108.htm |title=House of Lords Journal 237 (Session 2003-04) |accessdate=2009-04-13 |publisher=www.parliament.uk}}</ref>

==Life==
He was born in [[Sangol]],<ref Name=post>{{cite web |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2005/01/09/story1425.asp |title=Rana's relief  |accessdate=2009-04-13 |publisher=The Sunday Business Post}}</ref> [[India]] and is the oldest sibling of three brothers and two sisters.

Rana left [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] in 1963 for [[England]],<ref Name=post/> but now has been a resident of [[Belfast]] since 1966. He had to repair his property portfolio over 25 times during [[the Troubles]] in Northern Ireland because of bombings and arson attacks.<ref Name=post/> "Being an Indian I should not have had any loyalty to Northern Ireland; I stayed there despite the problem," said Rana. Today, he is a successful property developer, hotelier and president of the Northern Ireland Chamber of Commerce and Industry. He is director of Andras House, is a leading figure in the Indian community in Northern Ireland. He is India's honorary consul in Belfast.<ref Name=post/>

Rana promotes business links between India and Northern Ireland and has been elected president of the Northern Ireland Chamber of Commerce. He led a trade mission of 13 companies to India to explore business opportunities for Northern Ireland companies.

==Awards and philanthropy==
Rana was awarded an MBE in 1996,<ref Name=post/> for his contribution to the economic regeneration of the city of Belfast through the development of hotels, restaurants, fashion shops and modern office accommodation. Rana has set up a charitable trust of Rs.50 million for a school and a college named Taxila, in his native village Sanghol, near Chandigarh, India. The new college has collaborative links with the [[University of Ulster]] in Northern Ireland.<ref Name=post/> The university conferred an honorary doctorate on Rana who led a delegation of academics from the university to India to explore educational partnerships and help develop university links between India and Northern Ireland. Rana also received an Honorary Doctorate from Bengal Engineering and Science University in West Bengal in November 2008.

==Disputes==
A dispute has continued for many years over the redevelopment plans of the Tillie & Henderson factory site in [[Derry]], this site is owned by Dijit Rana.<ref Name=tillie>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/foyle_and_west/7994002.stm |title=Call for action on Tillie's site |accessdate=2009-04-13 |publisher= BBC News | date=2009-04-10}}</ref> The site was previously a shirt factory of historic importance but was damaged in multiple arson attacks including major ones in 2001,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/1293916.stm |title='Arson' attack on factory |accessdate=2009-04-13 |publisher=BBC News | date=2001-04-24}}</ref> and 2002,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/2542129.stm |title=Former factory damaged in blaze |accessdate=2009-04-13 |publisher=BBC News | date=2002-12-04}}</ref> and was subsequently demolished without permission in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/radiofoyle/features/tillie.shtml |title=Tillie and Henderson |accessdate=2009-04-13 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> A budget hotel originally envisioned for the site was still at the planning stage in 2009.<ref Name=tillie/> Rana stated in April 2009 that his designers "we're trying to get things right this time", and communication was ongoing with the [[Northern Ireland Environment Agency]], and he hoped that "there will be a general welcome for our plans in what is a prime location in the city".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.derryjournal.com/journal/I-still-want-to-build.5165586.jp |title='I still want to build hotel on Tillie's site'- says Lord Rana |accessdate=2009-04-13 |date=13 April 2009 |publisher=www.derryjournal.com}}</ref>

Rana was forced to comply with an Urgent Works Notice in 2003 from the [[Department of the Environment (Northern Ireland)|Department of the Environment]]. It obliged him to carry out immediate repairs to [[Cairndhu House]], near [[Larne]]. Rana was advised that the building would be taken from him if he did not comply with the works notice.<ref Name=post/>

Rana himself states that he has protected a lot of heritage buildings in Belfast,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/lord-diljit-rana-past-heartbreak-for-hotel-tycoon-13461092.html |title=Lord Diljit Rana: Past heartbreak for hotel tycoon |accessdate=2009-04-13 |date=23 July 2007 | publisher=belfasttelegraph.co.uk}}</ref> including:
* The Oxford Street Church
* Andras House (built in 1889)
* The Lincoln Building
* Renshaws Hotel.

